while others lead to up to 100% higher energy production costs than fossil fuels. Employment effects of using biofuels are small but positive. (C) 2000 Elsevier Science Ltd. All rights reserved.The paper describes results of the BioCosts project in which a comprehensive analysis of the economic paper and environmental performance of the energy use of biomass was carried out for selected existing facilities throughout the European Union. It is demonstrated that the appropriately organized use of biofuels has significant environmental advantages compared to the use of fossil fuels. Mitigation of global warming is the largest single incentive, to use biofuels. However, only a few technologies are economically competitive under prevailing conditions, while others lead to up to 100% higher energy production costs than fossil fuels. Employment effects of using biofuels are small but positive.",,"Cost effectiveness; Fossil fuels; Global warming; Industrial economics; Biofuels; Biomass; biomass power; cost benefit analysis; energy use; European Union; Europe",,,,,,"Long-term integration of renewable energy sources into the European energy system (1998), Heidelberg: PhysicaTotal costs and benefits of biomass in selected regions of the European Union (BioCosts) (1998) Final Report to the European Commission (JOR3-CT95-0006), , Mannheim: Zentrum fur Europaischer Wirtschaftsforschung (ZEW); Hohmeyer, O., Walz, R., The analysis of indirect emissions due to imtermediate production (1992) Proceedings on an Expert Workshop on Life-Cycle Analysis-Methods and Experiences (Paris, May 21-22), pp. 228-237. , Paris: OECD; Vogels, S., Technischer Fortschritt und seine okonomischen und okologischen Folgen: Das Beispiel der Elektriziatswirtschaft von Baden-Wurttemberg Unpublished draft dissertation, University of OldenburgFinal Reports pf ExternE Phase III, 1-6. , http://ExternE.jrc.es, forth-coming; ExternE: Externalities of Energy, 1-6. , Luxembourg: Office for Official Publications of th